{{see|Ancien Régime}}
==English==

===Etymology===
French ''Ancient Régime'', ''Old Rule'', ''Old Order''; the word first appeared in English in print in 1794.

===Noun===
'''[[ancien]] [[régime]]''' (''plural:'' '''[[anciens régimes]]''')

# {{cattag|pejorative connotations}} A system of government long since supplanted by another; particularly a state of [[feudalism]] with an absolute [[monarchy]] supported by the doctrine of the [[Divine Right of Kings]] or [[天命]] with the explicit consent of an established [[church]].

----

==French==

===Noun===
'''[[ancien]] [[régime]]''' (''plural:'' '''[[anciens régimes]]''')

# A former government

===Usage notes===
The term is used generically in French to refer to any previous government, without automatic negative connotations.  In English, the term is generally used pejoratively.

